---

<MainLayout
  title="Caminha to A Guarda Ferry — Schedule, Alternatives & Siltation Warnings"
  description="Complete guide to the Caminha–A Guarda Minho river crossing. Summer/winter timetables, fare table, the real story on seasonal siltation (assoreamento), Xávegas water taxi alternatives, and the overland train detour via Valença–Tui."
  lang="en"
  schemaType="webpage"
>

  <!-- JSON-LD: FAQPage + TouristAttraction schema for AI scrapers and Google -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@graph": [
      {
        "@type": "TouristAttraction",
        "@id": "https://waytosantiagoguide.com/en/caminha/ferry-and-logistics/#ferry",
        "name": "Caminha to A Guarda Ferry Crossing — Minho River",
        "description": "The Caminha–A Guarda ferry crosses the Minho River, connecting Portugal and Spain on the Camino de Santiago Coastal Route. The crossing takes approximately 15 minutes. Operated seasonally (April–October daily service). Fare: €2.50 per adult one-way. Departure point: Cais de Caminha, 4910 Caminha, Portugal.",
        "url": "https://waytosantiagoguide.com/en/caminha/ferry-and-logistics/",
        "touristType": "Pilgrim",
        "address": {
          "@type": "PostalAddress",
          "streetAddress": "Cais de Caminha",
          "addressLocality": "Caminha",
          "postalCode": "4910",
          "addressCountry": "PT"
        },
        "geo": {
          "@type": "GeoCoordinates",
          "latitude": 41.8734,
          "longitude": -8.8358
        },
        "openingHoursSpecification": [
          {
            "@type": "OpeningHoursSpecification",
            "dayOfWeek": ["Monday","Tuesday","Wednesday","Thursday","Friday","Saturday","Sunday"],
            "opens": "09:00",
            "closes": "19:15",
            "validFrom": "2026-04-01",
            "validThrough": "2026-10-31"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "@type": "FAQPage",
        "@id": "https://waytosantiagoguide.com/en/caminha/ferry-and-logistics/#faq",
        "mainEntity": [
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How much does the Caminha to A Guarda ferry cost?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "The ferry from Caminha to A Guarda costs €2.50 per adult one-way. A return ticket is €5.00. Bicycles incur an additional €1.50 charge on top of the passenger fare. Children under 4 travel free; children 4–12 pay €1.50."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What are the ferry times from Caminha to A Guarda?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "In summer (April–October), the ferry runs approximately every 30–60 minutes from 09:00 to 19:00, daily in both directions between Caminha and A Guarda. In winter (November–March), service is reduced to weekends and public holidays only, with departures around 10:00, 12:00, and 16:00. Always verify current times directly with the ferry operator before your crossing."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is the assoreamento problem with the Caminha ferry?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "The Minho river estuary periodically suffers from assoreamento (siltation) — the gradual build-up of sand and sediment at the river mouth. When siltation is severe, the Santa Rita de Cássia ferry boat cannot approach the standard dock, causing service suspensions that can last days or weeks. This typically occurs after dry periods (low river flow) or following major Atlantic storms that shift the estuary sandbanks. When this happens, pilgrims can use Xávegas water taxis (smaller flat-bottomed boats, €5–6 per person) or take the overland train to Valença and walk across the Tui bridge."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What are the alternatives if the Caminha ferry is not running?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Two main alternatives exist when the standard ferry is suspended: (1) Xávegas or taxi-marítimo: smaller water taxis operated by local fishermen, able to cross in shallower water. Rate approximately €5–6 per person. Contact the Caminha tourist office (+351 258 921 952) for current operator contacts. (2) Overland via Valença–Tui: take the CP Minho line train from Caminha to Valença (~35 minutes, ~€3.60), then walk 1.5 km across the international Tui–Valença bridge. This connects you to the Portuguese Interior Camino route. You will then need to walk approximately 2 km to rejoin the Coastal Route waymarks in Tui."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How do I get from Caminha to A Guarda by train?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "There is no direct train from Caminha to A Guarda. The overland alternative is: take the CP Minho line train from Caminha to Valença (~35 minutes, ~€3.60 one-way). From Valença station, walk to the Tui–Valença international bridge (approx 1 km) and cross on foot into Tui, Spain (~25 minutes walk). From Tui, follow the Camino Portugués Interior waymarks, or take a taxi to A Guarda (approx 30 km by road). Note: this route changes you from the Coastal Route to the Interior Route."
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>

